I"K<h2 id="use-short-passwords-on-macos-big-sur-four-characters-not-required">Use Short Passwords On MacOS Big Sur. FOUR Characters Not Required.</h2>

<p>If you’re an Apple user and have macOS Big Sur, Catalina or Mojave installed on your machine you’ve probably realized you can’t use a password shorter than 4 characters anymore…</p>

<p>Luckily, here is the easy fix.</p>

<h4 id="1-open-terminal-on-your-machine">1. Open “Terminal” on your machine.</h4>

<h4 id="2-type-this-command--press-return-enter">2. Type this command &amp; press Return (enter):</h4>
<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>`pwpolicy -clearaccountpolicies`
</code></pre></div></div>

<h4 id="3-terminal-will-ask-you-to-enter-the-password-for-your-admin-profile">3. Terminal will ask you to enter the password for your admin profile.</h4>
<p>Terminal WILL NOT show the password as you type it.
After typing the password for your account, press “Return” (enter).</p>

<h4 id="4-youre-all-done-yes-it-really-is-that-easy-now-just-go-into-your-system-preferences--users--groups--reset-your-password-to-any-password-youd-like">4. You’re all done! Yes, it really is that easy. Now, just go into your System Preferences &gt; Users &amp; Groups &amp; reset your password to any password you’d like.</h4>

